lians could think, feel, say, and write. Among the lessons taught by this music were that rules enforced by artistic tradition could be broken, that opera could jolt spectators into intense feeling even as it educated them, and that Italy could be in the vanguard of stylistic and technical innovation rather than clinging to the glories of centuries past. More practically, theatrical performances showed audiences that political change really was possible, making the newly engaged spectator in the opera house into an actor on the political stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aOperaxPolitical aspectszFrancezParisy19th century. 0aOperaxPolitical aspectszItalyy19th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh  aacting.  aactor.  aartist.  aclassical music.  acomposer.  acomposition.  adonizetti.  aemotions.  afiring squad.  ainnovation.  ainspiring.  aitalian art.  aitalian culture.  aitalian opera.  aitalian.  aitaly.  alife lessons.  amercadante.  amorals.  amusic.  amusical composer.  amusician.  aopera.  aperformance art.  apolitical protest.  arossini.  astage musical.  astage.  atradition.  averdi.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052027625340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096657440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966574423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966574/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles